the expenses of keeping Ludlow castle; re-seisin of Cottesmore, Rutland, taken from him by the earl of Chester.

his efforts in the matter between Hugh de Bolbec and Roger Bertram; the former refuses to surrender a castle to the latter; a safe-conduct for the king of Scots; a warrant for his absence since he is involved in an assize of 'darrein presentment'.

thanks him for his kindness; he has been ill and following advice from physicians he remains at home in order to improve his health; concerning the council held at York, he would be glad to know what took place.

request for the lands of Terric Tyes; asks that P. de Buiall', a clerk of the king of England, kept with him, be not harboured.

Though detained on the road by illness, arrived at Rome on Tuesday before St Matthias' Day (17 February). On the same day gave the Pope John's letters at the Lateran. He asked after the state of the kingdom and has much rejoiced to hear that all was well with regard to the King's person.
Brian de Lisle's seisin of Laughton en le Morthen, Yorkshire. Mention is also made of William Basset as seneschal of the said Brian.
he is not able to obey the king's command and come to the council because his mother is ill; prays that another day be appointed.
recommendation for William de Worcester.

the King ordered the bishop to have the amercements of his eyre in Yorkshire and Northumberland to be fixed by the sheriff and two lawful knights of each county. Accordingly he delivered the amercements to be collected, in writing, to the sheriff of Northumberland before Lent, and to the sheriff of York at the beginning of Lent, fixing last Easter as the term for payment at the Exchequer.
report of interview with Robert de Vieuxpont; the king's coronation; conduct the king of Scots and other magnates from the Tweed to York.
affairs of William of Lancaster.
the king of Scots will not enter York before the king of England.

the king of Scots is travelling towards York, he does not wish to enter York before Thursday - namely, he does not wish to enter before the king of England; the adjournment of a plea by writ of 'novel disseisin' between Colin de Quatremar', A.
the adjournment of a case for Robert de Ros who is waiting in northern parts to escort the king of Scots.
request for adjournment of case of novel disseisin for Robert Ros - he is to conduct the king of Scots.
liberties of the English church; king's journey to the Holy Land.
supplication to be consulted if action is contemplated on the manor of Feckenham, Worcestershire, granted to him by the late King John.
recommendation of Roger de Cruus; the surrender of Trim castle; he needs financial aid. Previously identified incorrectly in Lists and Indexes XV as Richard de Crus.

a certain woman, who held of Pembroke's knight, Roger de Hyde, died, and Roger took her fee into his hand, upon which the servants of Faukes de Breaute came and took one of his men and his carts and corn, and keeps them without replevin.

his lands attacked by Llywelyn, prince of North Wales, his castles of Netliebert and Wych demolished, his men there captured and compelled to make financial terms with Llywelyn for their safety; he requests the lands be restored, that he be enabled to rebuild his castles, that he be not hindered in prosecuting his rights on the morrow of St.
concerning the attacks and injuries from Llywelyn, he has not taken revenge. Concerning the castle of Fotheringay, co. Northampton, he will answer for all things on the morrow of the feast of St.

requests justice for John Marshal, his kinsman, and records the misdeeds of Faukes de Breaute against John.
requests justice for the bearer, Willaim de Brichevill, and that he may have replevin of his land in Hampshire of which he has been unjustly disseised by the king's letters.
inquest relating to William de Ros has not been made properly by Faukes de Breaute.
return of prisoners; English attacks; peace between them; Reynold de Braose.

his mission at Cologne; his request to return to England.
protection against the bishop of Durham.

report of the death of the earl of Hereford; he has taken the earl's lands in Gloucestershire into the king's hands.
the earl of Salisbury proposes to enter Berkeley castle, Gloucestershire.
he is in receipt of the justiciar's orders to delay demands concerning the debt to the Jews of Roger fitz Nicholas until the Nativity of the Blessed Virgin; desires to be further informed.
concerning the willingness of an 'approver' who was at Malmesbury.

they are unable to enquire into assarts in Harewood and Alveston forests because of the bailiffs of Savary de MaulÃ©on and Hugh de Vivon'. Damage; the name Acton' has been supplied.

concerning the collection of carrucage at York on the morrow of St. Giles; this has been refused by the earls, barons and all free men as it had not been duly asked for by the king; enquiries have been made of the king's demesne lands and the results will be transmitted to you in London at Michaelmas; most of the abbots have paid.
his undersheriff detained in Yorkshire; credence for J. Mildenhall.

greatly desire your aid against the oppressions of the lord of Parthenay and other strong men of our neighbourhood.
assistance to his attorney and S. Campio in a suit, as he cannot appear personally.
the death of John de Neville; letters of the king to the sheriffs of Notthigham and Lincoln so that the lands of the said John can be taken into the king's hands; homage for the lands.

Llywelyn, prince of North Wales sent a message to Pandulf on Christmas Eve last, excusing himself from appearing at Worcester on the morrow of the Epiphany, the day they had appointed for him, and begging for a new term, to Pandulf's greatest annoyance.

his meeting with Llywelyn and the Marchers in the octave of the Purification; the form of letters for the continuation of the truce between the king of England and the king of France; Exchequer business.

request that he send someone on the king's behalf to France to treat together with Master Peter de Collemedio, the pope's chaplain, concerning the prorogation of truces; also that he would provide a person to go to Poitou.
re-seisin for Margaret, daughter of Guy de Bretteville.

request that you be at Worcester on the morrow of the octaves of the Purification of the Blessed Virgin, the day appointed for Llywelyn, prince of North Wales. Given at Bristol and dated xiii Kalens of February.

a messenger from the count of Savoy arrived in the kingdom with a letter requesting provision for his son; the first revenues of the vacant church of Combe were granted to the son of the count of Savoy notwithstanding subsequent letters received from Hubert.
stand firm against dissidents who are flocking to London; appoint a suitable man to go to Poitou; meeting with Llywelyn at Worcester. Given at Malmesbury and dated viiii Kalens of February.
concerning the affairs of Roger Bertram. Given at Malmsbury and dated viii Kalens of February.
he is returning to London from Wales. Given at Cirencester and dated iii Kalens February.
because of urgent business of the king and kingdom he is hastening to London. Given at Haynes and dated ii Kalens February.
he is coming to Windsor; the earl marshal is forbidden to fortify the castle of Marlborough, Wiltshire. Given at Merton and dated iii Nones of April.
the case between William de Warenne, earl of Surrey and Robert de Vieuxpont concerning the countess of Eu to be adjourned. Given at Dunstable and dated as vi Kalens of May.
injuries done to the sheriff of York is an act of contempt. Given at Lincoln and dated the nones of June.
recommendation for Robert de Ferrars, crusader. Given at Lanthony by Gloucester.
appointment to enquire whether he should entertain an appeal from the court of the bishop of Coventry in a case of R de Cheney v. Ankettle the Templar.

gives an opinion of Philip de Oldcoates (Ulecot); the banning of tournaments; his itinery. Given at Cerne Abbas and dated viii Kalens of September.
concerns over Poitou; he has received letters and awaits Hubert's arrival.Given at Sherborne and dated as vii Kalens of September.
protection for Robert fitz Walter, crusader. Given at London.
Walter Crek wishes to enter a religious house; he has quit claimed his lands to his son and wishes him to be in the custody of William Briwerre. Given at Downton and dated as iiii Kalens of January.

directing the issue of a writ for the resumption of an assize of darrein presentment of the church of Farley, the Legate having vainly attempted to bring the parties to terms. Given at Wilton and dated as ii Kalens of January.
advice on negotiations at the Roman court; repay merchants of Sienna.
the seige of Rochefort-sur-Loire; he has been summoned to Bordeaux; credence for Theobald, Crispin's chaplain.
the men of his hundred are keeping back their rents.
the siege of Rochfort-sur-Loire; help has been refused by the vicomte of Thouars and Hugh de Lusignan.
enforcement of an agreement between Philip the Miller and the prior of Lanthony, made when he was justiciar.
the need for a skilled lawyer in Poitou; the proposed marriage of Hugh de Lusignan; the truce with France was broken by the French; the siege of Rochefort-sur-Loire.
his annual pension; assistance for defence of Rochefort-sur-Loire.

thanks him for ordering Engelard de Cigony by the King's letters to restore the cattle of the Abbot of Reading and clerks of his bailiwick, seised because their [--] were not [--]. He will not obey either the King's or the Bishop's order.
he is sending his chamberlain to ask for his help in respect of the injustice and offences committed by protest against the actions of Engelard de Cigony and his bailiffs.

thanking him for the reception of their messenger Merletus de Frigido Monte and for advising the king to confirm their freedom from tolls at Bordeaux. They beg him to induce the king to make them a grant towards fortifying their town; to write to the archbishop of Auch and the abbot of Blasimon to encourage them in forwarding the crusade; to write to the bishop of Lectoure to look after his interests in Lomagne since the Cardinal has been forcing his citizens of Lectoure and knights of Lomagne to make oath to the Count of Montfort, saving the king of England, notwithstanding that the Count of Toulouse had never any lordship in those places and that the Pope's letters on behalf of Henry III have been shown to him.
concerning the tolls at Bordeaux; assistance for the fortification of the town of La RÃ©ole; credence for Merlet de Frigido Monte, burgess. Document much stained.

procedure following the death of the archbishop of Bordeaux.

Hugh de Balliol hinders him from restoring the castle of Mitford until his rights in the manor of Mere, detained by the earl of Salisbury, are restored to him; he has threatened to withdraw from the king's service; request for restoration of these rights.

he has been ordered by letters of the king to destroy his castle of Harbottle, Northumberland; explains its site in the Scottish march, its use to the kingdom both in times of war and peace; request that the king be informed that the castle is not adulterine.
he has been summoned to Portsmouth for service overseas, but will be delayed.
the value of Thurstan Banastre's lands; the heir to these is married to the daughter of Philip de Orreby, justiciar of Chester.

the bearer, Sir James de Scuidemor', will inform him on his return what they have done in the affair of the earl of Salisbury, and in that of his nephew, Roger Bertram in Northumberland, and elsewhere.
the legate has seized the lands of the late king John's chaplain Henry, who ought to have a crusaders protection.
concerning the miners at Tynedale mines, appurtenant to Carlisle castle, Cumberland, and Hugh de Balliol's interference.
transcript of bull of pope Honorius III concerning king's minority and declaring him to be of age.
a request for Richard Phitun, constable of Richmond, to allow the king's miners to work Swaledale mines.
he wishes to prolong his stay in England; requests that H. Chacepore, his nephew, should have the daughter of Thomas Basset who is the widow of William Malet.
concerning payments due from the burgesses of Newcastle-upon-Tyne, Northumberland; timber from the bishop of Durham; monetary values given.
concerning forest business in Hereford and the Marches.

he is forced to call upon de Burgh for money which he and Sir William the Marshal were sureties, since he must pay the earl of Arundel Â£100 which he owes him at his setting out at Midsummer; and he has likewise long been in de Burgh's debt for the money he lent him in his great affair.

the justiciar will be glad to hear that the countess of Eu, the earl's niece, and the justiciar's cousin, has arrived in England, and that they have spoken with the king. He has appointed them a day, the Octave of the Nativity of Our Lady, wheresoever he may be.
his land at Leaden Roding, Essex, has been taken into the king's hands after it was sold by Maud de Blancmuster; adjournment of the case concerning this.
the proposed truce between Amaury and the king of France; the visit of Geoffrey de Neville to Poitou. Damaged document.
Philip d'Albigny, constable of Devizes, has ignored instructions to restore his lands; financial difficulty in redeeming his lands in Poitou.

he has received writs ordering him to give Robert Marmion, junior, who has returned to his allegience, seisin of his lands; Robert de Mortimer, and his men, and Ralph Tirel, constable of Pevensey, and his men, will not allow Robert Marmion to possess his lands in peace.
lists that all money due to her for her dower made with the late King John at this present term of All Saints and other terms past, may be paid to the bearer, a Cistercian monk named Walter.

asks that in consideration of his services to King John and King Henry III and for his future services, they will give or lend him 12 marks of the king's money at Niort in the keeping of Peter Bonet and Emery the moneyer.

the countess of Huntingdon, widow of the Earl David, complains that the baliff and servants of William Marshal ejected her from her lands, namely, from the manor of Bathewe, which is of her marriage portion, and from Tottenham and the manor of Kemston, which are of her dower.

the King's bailiffs and his report that they cannot distrain upon those who have taken the cross for the King's debts since they apply to the deans and chaplains of the district who put the bailiffs under excommunication and interdict.

his suspension from chapter and choir for repeated absences after warning.

thanks the bishop for protecting his men and lands and begs he will continue to do so. On Tuesday after Candlemas (5 February 1219) the Christian army crossed the Nile which runs under Damietta between them and the infidels.
payment of his indemnity; attacks by English sailors on men of Calais and elsewhere.
letter of credence for Florence le Riche, his chamberlain, and lay brother H Convers.

on his way home from Gloucester he fell dangerously ill at Nottingham so that he had much ado to get to Rufford Abbey and at last after many days to his manor of Scroby where their messenger, Ralph de Norwich, found him.
Asks them to do what they can for Albin O'Molloy, the bishop of Ferns, according to the letters of King John which he has. Not having his own seal, he has appended that of William de Cantelope.
a tournament at Staines, after the feast of Michaelmas.
his dispute with the monks of Durham.

the bishop ought to know that travellers near Winchester are robbed and even murdered. This is discreditable to the King, and the legate lays it on the bishop's conscience to have it ammended at once.
assistance for the bearers, crusaders. Given at Selborne and dated as iiii Kalens of July.
actions of the constable of Tickhill; request to delay discussions on the affairs of the countess of Eu. Given at Doncaster and dated as iiii Kalens of September.
demand to William Marshal, earl of Pembroke, for the castle of Fotheringay, co Northants; Pandulf is going to negotiate with the King of Scots. Given at Stamford and dated as viii Ides of October.
He has given orders from the bishop and himself to Walter Mauclerc to assist the sheriffs in levying the amercements. Asks the bishop to issue the necessary writs to them.

encloses a letter from his servant Landon, who keeps his prebend of'Burn', and trusts that the bishop and justiciar will mete out exemplary punishment for the insult done through him to Pandulf and to the King.

he has previously discussed with them the immoderate interest exacted by the Jews contrary to the decrees of the lateran Council. The abbot and convent of Westminster now complain that Isaac of Norwich is suing them for unlawful interest before the Justices of the Jews.
request for letters to be sent on behalf of the king, to the king of France and to P. de Collemedio, the pope's chaplain, concerning the prorogation of truce with France.
temporalities to be released to the new bishop of Ely. Given at Wells and dated as xvii Kalens of February.
discussions with Alan Martel, master of the Temple in England and a Templar representing the king of France. Given at Wenlock and dated the Nones of July.
Peter de Orreby has asked Pandulf for the custody of the land held by the late Thurstan Banastre whose son has married the daughter of the said Philip.
request that Nicholas is not molested in his office of chamberlain of London. Given at Haywood and dated the Ides of July.
As he was passing through Nottinghamshire and Derbyshire the inhabitants asked him to save for them the corn grown on the assarts which has been taken from them into the king's hands.
the garrisoning of Marlborough castle during King's absence in Yorkshire. Privy Seal letter given at Dunstable.

As Stephen de Segrave and Master Robert de Avenis will inform him, Pandulf has concluded satisfactorily the king's business with the king of Scots and is making haster to join him in order to have his advice on this and other matters.
certificate concerning an abjuror of the realm.

they have taken an inquisition on the orders of the bishop and justiciar into the detention of the houses at Southampton of Richard de Scankawilla, a knight of Sir Engelard de Cigosne (Sygony), keeper of the honor of Windsor, and the wrong done to him there.
request that the house in Bristol of Abraham the Jew, in the hands of the king, be granted to the use of Sogernel, a royal courier.

English affairs at the Roman court.
credence for P. de Aveill', bearer, on Irish business.

begs him to order the King's bailiffs of Northamptonshire to cease from demanding 20 marks for a debt of William de Duston, out of the wardship of William's lands, the grant of which the justiciar obtained for her.
deprivation of temporalities of archbishop of Canterbury; promotion of chancellor to bishopric of Durham.
he requires money owed to him from co. Norfolk to ransom Ralph his son.

request for the presentation of Combe church, Oxfordfordshire, valued at ten marks, to my clerk Walter who served the late king John.
his inability to provision the castle of Plymton, Devon due to Robert de Courtenay's arrest of the goods being shipped there; requests that Robert be ordered to allow the provisioning.

request to be excused from forest business to do his work at the Exchequer.

peace between the kings of England and France. Dated at Paris as vii Ides of May.

asks him to give seisin of her lands to Eustace de Es and not to believe Eustace, her son's servant.

the king has received de Burgh's gift of palfreys and admires them; Hubert's relationship to the king.
